hat would also not be fair to him intellectually. Ugh, I can't win. Then I think, what's so bad about being challenged a little socially? I feel It will definitely make him who he turns out to be which is why this choice is so agonizing. What's the worst that can happen if he doesn't fit in socially? Would that make him a riskier teen? Trying to impress the older kids to fit in? What about self-esteem not making the sports teams due to size? But what's wrong with a little adversity? Maybe he would be more motivated than if everything fell into his lap. In addition to being smart, he is really good looking if I do say so myself ...so I feel like if he was held back then everything would fall into his lap without really having to try very hard for it (really smart, normal size, good looking). Versus (small, socially awkward, normal bright intelligence). &#10;So my inclination is it start him on time and hope for the best. Worst Birthday Ever."/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1257" language="en" documentId="5126" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="subcouth" date="04/03/2012" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a32503567/yet_another_redshirting_debate?cpg=8" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5126" notes="" title="Yet another redshirting debate"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1171"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="1172" end="1257"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>